{{Politics of Chile}}
The '''Political Constitution of the Republic of Chile of 1980''' ({{Lang-es|Constitución Política de la República de Chile}}) is the [[Constitution|fundamental law]] in force in [[Chile]]. It was approved and promulgated under the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973–1990)|military dictatorship]] headed by [[Augusto Pinochet]], being ratified by the Chilean citizenry through a [[1980 Chilean constitutional referendum|referendum]] on September 11, 1980, although being held under restrictions and without electoral registers. While 69% of the population was reported to have voted yes, the vote was questioned by hundreds of denunciations of irregularities and fraud. <ref>{{Cite web |last=Krause |first=Charles A. |date=September 12, 1980 |title=Pinochet Wins Overwhelming Vote on New Constitution |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/09/12/pinochet-wins-overwhelming-vote-on-new-constitution/750660cc-4fa3-4962-8720-9c4bddb2b595/ |website=Washington Post}}</ref> The constitutional text took effect, in a transitory regime, on March 11, 1981, and then entered into full force on March 11, 1990, with the [[Chilean transition to democracy|return to electoral democracy]]. It was amended for the first time in 1989 (through a [[1989 Chilean constitutional referendum|referendum]]), and afterward in 1991, 1994, 1997, each year from 1999 to 2001, 2003, each year from 2007 to 2015, and each year from 2017 to 2021, with the last three amendments concerning the constituent process of 2020–2022. In September 2005, under [[Ricardo Lagos]]'s presidency, a large amendment of the Constitution was approved by parliamentarians, removing from the text some of the less democratic dispositions coming from Pinochet's regime, such as [[Senator for life|senators-for-life]] and appointed senators, as well as the [[Military of Chile|armed forces]]' warranty of the [[Democracy|democratic]] regime.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Constitutional history of Chile |url=https://constitutionnet.org/country/constitutional-history-chile |access-date=2023-07-05 |website=ConstitutionNet |language=en}}</ref>

On November 15, 2019, following a [[2019–2021 Chilean protests|series of popular protests in October 2019]], a political agreement between parties with parliamentary representation called for a national referendum on the proposal of writing a new Constitution and on the mechanism to draft it.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cuffe |first1=Sandra |title=Chile agrees to hold referendum on constitution: 5 things to know |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/15/chile-agrees-to-hold-referendum-on-constitution-5-things-to-know |work=www.aljazeera.com |language=en}}</ref> A [[2020 Chilean national plebiscite|plebiscite]] held on October 25, 2020, approved drafting a new fundamental charter, as well as choosing by popular vote delegates to a [[Constitutional Convention (Chile)|Constitutional Convention]] which was to fulfill this objective. The members of the convention were [[2021 Chilean Constitutional Convention election|elected in May, 2021]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sherwood |first1=Dave |last2=Cambero |first2=Fabian |last3=Laing |first3=Aislinn |title=Chile's govt in shock loss as voters pick independents to draft constitution |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/chile-ruling-coalition-heading-disappointment-constitutional-delegates-vote-2021-05-17/ |work=Reuters |date=17 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref> and first convened on July 4, 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last1=W |first1=Daniela Mohor |title=How to write a new constitution for a divided and unequal Chile |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2021/07/04/americas/chile-constitution-assembly-intl-latam/index.html |work=CNN |date=4 July 2021 |language=en}}</ref> However, on 4 September 2022, voters rejected the new constitution in the [[2022 Chilean constitutional referendum|constitutional referendum]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chile constitution: Voters overwhelmingly reject radical change |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-62792025 |work=BBC News |date=5 September 2022}}</ref>

==Legitimacy==
{{expand section|date=January 2015}}
{{See also|1980 Chilean constitutional referendum}}
According to the law professor Camel Cazor Aliste, the Constitution of 1980 has problems of legitimacy stemming from two facts. First, the constitutional commission was not representative of the [[political spectrum]] of Chile: its members had been handpicked by the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973–90)|Pinochet dictatorship]], and opponents of the regime had been deliberately excluded. Secondly, the constitution's approval was achieved by the government in a controversial and tightly controlled referendum in 1980.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Cazor Aliste |first=Camel |date=2000 |title=Democracia y constitucion en Chile |url=http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518062933/http://mingaonline.uach.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-09502000000100003&script=sci_arttext |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-05-18 |journal=[[Revista de Derecho]] |publisher=[[Austral University of Chile]] |volume=IX |pages=25–34 |access-date=30 April 2015 }}</ref> Campaigning for the referendum was irregular, with the government calling people to vote positively on the reform, and also using radio and television commercial spots, while the opposition urging people to vote negatively were only able of doing small public demonstrations, without access to television time and limited radio access. There was no electoral roll for this vote, as the register had been burned during the dictatorship. There were multiple cases of double voting, with at least 3000 CNI agents doing so.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2012 |title=Revelan fraude en plebiscito de constitución de 1980 |url=http://www.lanacion.cl/revelan-fraude-en-plebiscito-que-aprobo-constitucion-de-1980/noticias/2012-06-11/115506.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304201711/http://www.lanacion.cl/revelan-fraude-en-plebiscito-que-aprobo-constitucion-de-1980/noticias/2012-06-11/115506.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-03-04  |publisher=[[La Nación (Chile)]] }}</ref>

Since the return to democracy, the constitution has been amended nearly 60 times.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Venice Commission :: Council of Europe |url=https://www.venice.coe.int/webforms/documents/default.aspx?pdffile=CDL-AD(2022)004- |access-date=2023-07-05 |website=www.venice.coe.int}}</ref>

A document from September 13, 1973, shows that [[Jaime Guzmán]] had by then already been tasked by the Junta to study the creation of a new constitution.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Los informes secretos de la CIA sobre Jaime Guzmán|url=https://www.elmostrador.cl/noticias/pais/2013/11/05/los-informes-secretos-de-la-cia-sobre-jaime-guzman/|last=Basso Prieto|first=Carlos|date=2013-11-05|access-date=2021-09-29|work=[[El Mostrador]]}}</ref>

It has been argued the 1980 Constitution was designed to favor the election of [[Right-wing political parties|right-wing]] legislative majorities. Several rounds of constitutional amendments have been enacted since 1989 to address this concern.<ref>Carey, John M. [https://cpb-us-e1.wpmucdn.com/sites.dartmouth.edu/dist/2/109/files/2013/02/Malapportionment-and-ideological-bias-in-Chilean-electoral-districts.pdf Malapportionment and ideological bias in Chilean electoral districts.] Dartmouth College. May 18, 2015.</ref><ref>Carey, John. [https://theglobalamericans.org/2015/05/chiles-electoral-reform/ Chile’s electoral reform.] Global Americans. May 27, 2015.</ref>

==Replacement==
In July 2022, a [[2022 proposed Political Constitution of the Republic of Chile|proposed replacement constitution]] was submitted for national debate and general [[2022 Chilean constitutional referendum|referendum]], but it was rejected on September 4 despite having had the support of left-leaning President [[Gabriel Boric]].<ref> [https://edition.cnn.com/2022/09/04/americas/chile-constitution-vote-intl/index.html CNN: Chilean voters overwhelmingly reject proposed leftist constitution ]</ref>

On March 6, 2023, a group of experts appointed by Congress began a second attempt to prepare a preliminary draft of a new constitution. The group, with lawyer [[Veronica Undurraga]] serving as its president, was scheduled to work for three months on 12 institutional bases agreed to by lawmakers, after which the draft would be given to an elected Constitutional Council, whose members would be voted upon on May 7, 2023. At the same time, a 14-member Technical Admissibility Committee began serving as arbitrator.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ramos |first=Natalia |date=2023-03-06 |title=Chile starts second attempt to draft new constitution |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/chile-starts-second-attempt-draft-new-constitution-2023-03-06/ |access-date=2023-07-26}}</ref>

